The paper proposes a framework for feature selection in tree models, which is a common problem in machine learning. The paper discusses the application of the framework on random forest and boosted trees, which are popular tree models used in various domains such as computer vision (cs.CV), natural language processing (cs.CL), and robotics (cs.RO). The paper also mentions the ability of tree models to handle various data types and complexities, which is a characteristic of machine learning models used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and data mining (cs.DM). Finally, the paper presents experimental results to validate the proposed framework, which is a common practice in machine learning research in the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
